    explanation: "Stokes shift (after George Gabriel Stokes, 1852): After photon absorption, the fluorophore undergoes rapid vibrational relaxation (losing energy to the environment) before emitting a photon. Therefore, emitted photons have lower energy (longer wavelength) than absorbed photons — e.g., FITC absorbs at ~495 nm, emits at ~519 nm; DAPI absorbs at ~360 nm, emits at ~460 nm. Larger Stokes shift = easier to separate excitation from emission. The optical setup: excitation filter (selects specific wavelengths) → dichromatic (dichroic) mirror (reflects excitation, transmits emission) → emission filter (blocks residual excitation). Autofluorescence (from cellular components like NADH, flavins) is a common source of background noise."
