    question: "In super-resolution microscopy, the concept of 'PSF engineering' is central to STED and related techniques. What does PSF stand for, and why is it critical to understanding resolution?",
    options: ["Photon Scattering Factor — describes how many photons are scattered per fluorophore excitation event, determining signal-to-noise ratio", "Point Spread Function — the 3D intensity distribution produced by a point source of light imaged through an optical system; for a perfect diffraction-limited microscope it approximates an Airy disk pattern (first zero at r = 0.61λ/NA). The PSF defines the smallest resolvable detail — two points are resolved when their PSFs no longer significantly overlap (Rayleigh criterion)", "Phase Shift Factor — the optical path difference introduced by the specimen at each pixel, forming the basis of phase contrast imaging", "Polarization State Function — describes the polarization ellipse of light emitted by each fluorophore, used in polarization anisotropy imaging"],
    answer: 1,
    explanation: "PSF (Point Spread Function): mathematical description of how a perfect point source is imaged by the microscope system. In 2D, the in-focus PSF of a diffraction-limited system is an Airy pattern: central disk (Airy disk) surrounded by concentric rings. Airy disk radius r = 0.61λ/NA (Rayleigh criterion for resolution). In 3D, the PSF extends into an elongated shape (PSF is ~3× wider in Z than XY). STED reduces the effective PSF by de-exciting peripheral fluorophores → smaller PSF → better resolution. Deconvolution algorithms computationally sharpen the measured image by 'inverting' the PSF. PSF measurement: subresolution fluorescent beads (100 nm) or fluorescent nanodiamonds. Aberrations (spherical, chromatic, astigmatism) distort PSF shape."
