    question: "Polarization microscopy is used to image birefringent specimens. Birefringence refers to:",
    options: ["The ability of a specimen to fluoresce when excited with polarized light, emitting photons perpendicular to the excitation polarization", "The property of an ordered material (crystals, collagen fibers, mitotic spindle) to have different refractive indices for light polarized along different axes (ne ≠ no) — causing the two orthogonal components of polarized light to travel at different speeds, creating retardation and interference when recombined at the analyzer", "The non-uniform scattering of white light into spectral components by an ordered specimen, creating visible color without staining", "The ability of a specimen to rotate the plane of polarized light through specific angles that can be measured to determine molecular chirality"],
    answer: 1,
    explanation: "Birefringence (double refraction): ordered specimens have two principal refractive indices (extraordinary ne and ordinary no). A polarizer passes linearly polarized light into the specimen → birefringent material splits it into two orthogonally polarized beams traveling at different velocities → path difference (retardation) = (ne - no) × specimen thickness → analyzer (crossed with polarizer at 90°) passes only the component of retarded light that has been rotated. Retardation Γ = λ/4 → maximum brightness (quarter-wave retardation). Birefringent structures: collagen, bone, cellulose, myosin in muscle, amyloid fibers, calcite crystals, mitotic spindle (starch-free mounting needed). Applications: geological thin sections, malaria hemozoin detection, amyloid diagnosis (Congo red + birefringence → apple-green), muscle physiology."
